## Suggested commit message (for the user to run manually)

```
refactor(llm): rename LLM adapter crates + types to wire-format-neutral names

The vendor name "OpenAI" was leaking into the type names, module
names, and constant names of both LLM adapter crates, making the
codebase feel married to one vendor and obscuring the actual
protocol each crate implements. This commit renames the public
surface of the LLM plugin crates to the wire format each one
talks, not the vendor that originated the format.

afa-plugin-llm-openai-compat -> afa-plugin-llm-chat-completions
  (the older /chat/completions wire format, supported by every
  OpenAI-compatible vendor: Groq, Cerebras, Ollama /v1, LM
  Studio, llama.cpp, vLLM, freellmapi, etc.)
afa-plugin-llm-http (unchanged crate name — already vendor-neutral;
  it targets the OpenAI Responses API by design)
  src/openai_adapter.rs -> src/responses_adapter.rs
  struct OpenAiAdapter   -> struct ResponsesAdapter
  struct OpenAiConfig    -> struct ResponsesConfig
  const OPENAI_PROD_BASE_URL -> const OPENAI_RESPONSES_BASE_URL
  fn   map_request_to_openai -> fn   map_request_to_responses
  preset gpt_4o          -> preset responses_gpt_4o

afa-plugin-llm-chat-completions (the renamed compat crate):
  const OPENAI_CHAT_PROD_BASE_URL -> const OPENAI_CHAT_COMPLETIONS_BASE_URL
  default provider_name  "openai-prod" -> "chat-completions-prod"
  test SecretRef.name    "openai-prod-key" -> "chat-completions-prod-key"
  test SecretRef.name    "openai-compat-test-key" -> "chat-completions-test-key"

The "OpenAI" name is preserved in:
- doc-block story-telling comments that describe the protocol
  ("OpenAI Responses API", "OpenAI Chat Completions API") — these
  are accurate descriptions of the wire format, not misleading
  type names
- the test key_name "openai-prod-key" in the http crate, which
  literally represents the OpenAI production key the operator
  pre-seals (this crate talks to OpenAI only; the chat-completions
  crate talks to any compatible vendor so the provider_name was
  misleading there)
- the `afa-contracts::llm::capabilities` doc-comment example, which
  now uses ResponsesConfig
- the `afa-llm::tests::llm_v1` doc-comment example, which now
  mentions ResponsesAdapter as the concrete adapter

Validation: 218/218 tests pass, clippy clean, doc builds.

Phase 2 work (streaming.rs + adapter_streaming.rs in both sibling
crates, conformance.rs in afa-llm) is included in this commit —
it was the unstaged follow-up from the previous session. The two
phases are atomic w.r.t. each other (Phase 2 imports Phase 1.5/2
types).

Follow-up: async-openai = "0.29" is still in
afa-plugin-llm-http/Cargo.toml. It is unused (raw reqwest does
the transport). Drop in Phase 3 cleanup.
```

The user executes the commit manually per project memory.

## Next step (Phase 3) preview

Phase 3 = tool calls + describe_capabilities caching. Tracked in
IMPL-llm-engine-baseline.md §5 (NOT STARTED). When the user is
ready, this handoff becomes the resume point — the agent should:

1. Read `docs/features/llm-engine-baseline/IMPL-llm-engine-baseline.md`
   §5 in full before planning.
2. Decide whether tool calls go in `afa-contracts::llm` (the
   type-only crate) or in a new helper crate. Per the
   "sibling-crate" pattern, a new helper would be the
   `afa-llm-internal` crate that absorbs the `key_wiring.rs`
   duplication noted in project memory.
3. Drop the `async-openai` dep as part of Phase 3 (or earlier, as
   a separate cleanup commit if the user prefers).
4. The `afa-plugin-llm-claude` adapter (also in the backlog)
   becomes a copy-paste of `afa-plugin-llm-http` with a
   different wire format and a different `key_wiring` (Anthropic
   uses a different auth header — `x-api-key` + `anthropic-version`
   instead of `Authorization: Bearer`).
